PBS - Ocean Adventures - Voyage to Kure 1 of 2 (2005)


Information

Stretching more than 1,200 miles from Honolulu, the chain of islands and atolls known as the Northwestern Hawaiian Islands (NWHI) is one of the most remote places on Earth. Home to one of the largest coral reef systems in the world -- nearly as vast as Australia&#039;s Great Barrier Reef - the NWHI archipelago composed of 10 islands and more than 100 reefs and shoals.

They create a rich tropical marine environment and form the foundation of an ecosystem that hosts more than 7,000 species, including marine mammals, fishes, sea turtles, birds and invertebrates. Many are rare, threatened or endangered. At least a quarter of them can be found nowhere else on Earth. They are protected by America&#039;s largest National Wildlife Refuge, open only to scientists.
